\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {BenchCAD versus prior CAD code-generation work.} BenchCAD is designed as a \emph  {unified, capability-decomposed evaluation framework} for large-model CAD reasoning, intended to remain useful as the field evolves from current frontier MLLMs (GPT-5.3, Claude Opus 4.7, $\ldots  $) toward future CAD agents and generative systems. It is distinct in purpose from the prior CadQuery-VLM lineage (CAD-Recode, cadrille, CADEvolve), which primarily releases training corpora alongside small fine-tuned models (Qwen 1.5B--2B) that saturate near $\sim $92\% IoU on legacy sketch+extrude test splits. \textbf  {Columns:} \textbf  {Type}: \emph  {corpus+model} = training corpus released with a fine-tuned model, \emph  {benchmark} = held-out evaluation suite, \emph  {dataset} = mixed-purpose CAD design dataset; \textbf  {\#Indus.\ fam.} = named industrial part families with explicit functional identity (gear, drill, spring, $\ldots  $) versus untyped CAD parts pooled without semantic structure; \textbf  {\#Std codes} = distinct ISO/DIN/EN/ASME/IEC specification codes from which parameter ranges are programmatically sampled; \textbf  {\#Distinct CQ ops} = distinct CadQuery API operations exercised in the released dataset (counts derived from each work's published description; ours from a static analysis of the released family code, see Appendix~\ref {app:ops}); \textbf  {Adv ops} = whether all four advanced operation families (helix, loft/sweep, twist-extrude, parametric involute-gear construction) are exercised; \textbf  {\#Eval} = distinct models reported in the original work's evaluation. BenchCAD additionally introduces a 6-orientation rotation-invariant $64^3$ IoU $\geq 0.99$ verification protocol and ratio-only scale-invariant prompts (\S  \ref {sec:dataset}, \S  \ref {sec:tasks}). {\fontfamily  {pzd}\fontencoding  {U}\fontseries  {m}\fontshape  {n}\selectfont  \char 51}$\,$ = supported, part.\, = partial, -- = absent.}}{6}{table.1}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:cmp_prior}{{1}{6}{\textbf {BenchCAD versus prior CAD code-generation work.} BenchCAD is designed as a \emph {unified, capability-decomposed evaluation framework} for large-model CAD reasoning, intended to remain useful as the field evolves from current frontier MLLMs (GPT-5.3, Claude Opus 4.7, $\ldots $) toward future CAD agents and generative systems. It is distinct in purpose from the prior CadQuery-VLM lineage (CAD-Recode, cadrille, CADEvolve), which primarily releases training corpora alongside small fine-tuned models (Qwen 1.5B--2B) that saturate near $\sim $92\% IoU on legacy sketch+extrude test splits. \textbf {Columns:} \textbf {Type}: \emph {corpus+model} = training corpus released with a fine-tuned model, \emph {benchmark} = held-out evaluation suite, \emph {dataset} = mixed-purpose CAD design dataset; \textbf {\#Indus.\ fam.} = named industrial part families with explicit functional identity (gear, drill, spring, $\ldots $) versus untyped CAD parts pooled without semantic structure; \textbf {\#Std codes} = distinct ISO/DIN/EN/ASME/IEC specification codes from which parameter ranges are programmatically sampled; \textbf {\#Distinct CQ ops} = distinct CadQuery API operations exercised in the released dataset (counts derived from each work's published description; ours from a static analysis of the released family code, see Appendix~\ref {app:ops}); \textbf {Adv ops} = whether all four advanced operation families (helix, loft/sweep, twist-extrude, parametric involute-gear construction) are exercised; \textbf {\#Eval} = distinct models reported in the original work's evaluation. BenchCAD additionally introduces a 6-orientation rotation-invariant $64^3$ IoU $\geq 0.99$ verification protocol and ratio-only scale-invariant prompts (\S \ref {sec:dataset}, \S \ref {sec:tasks}). \cmark $\,$ = supported, part.\, = partial, -- = absent}{table.1}{}}
