\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Per-model performance across the four BenchCAD task categories} (frontier proprietary subset; open-source baselines reported in Table~\ref {tab:main_eval}). Bar style encodes the task (CodeGen IoU, CodeEdit, QA-img, QA-code); colour encodes model family (GPT in green, Claude in orange, Gemini in purple); within-family variants distinguish thinking vs.\ non-thinking modes. Two patterns stand out and motivate the diagnostics that follow: (i) the QA-img bar is consistently lower than QA-code for every model (the \emph  {Vision Bottleneck}, \S  \ref {sec:exp_capability}), and (ii) the CodeEdit bar trails CodeGen on every model despite editing being intuitively easier than greenfield generation, reflecting the \emph  {Edit Leakage} effect (\S  \ref {sec:exp_edit}).}}{13}{figure.4}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:main_results}{{4}{13}{\textbf {Per-model performance across the four BenchCAD task categories} (frontier proprietary subset; open-source baselines reported in Table~\ref {tab:main_eval}). Bar style encodes the task (CodeGen IoU, CodeEdit, QA-img, QA-code); colour encodes model family (GPT in green, Claude in orange, Gemini in purple); within-family variants distinguish thinking vs.\ non-thinking modes. Two patterns stand out and motivate the diagnostics that follow: (i) the QA-img bar is consistently lower than QA-code for every model (the \emph {Vision Bottleneck}, \S \ref {sec:exp_capability}), and (ii) the CodeEdit bar trails CodeGen on every model despite editing being intuitively easier than greenfield generation, reflecting the \emph {Edit Leakage} effect (\S \ref {sec:exp_edit})}{figure.4}{}}
