\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {The generalisation gap on BenchCAD remains substantial, even after 25k SFT steps.} Qwen2-VL-2B trained on three data mixtures under matched 9 GPU-hour budgets and evaluated throughout the 0--25k step horizon on the BenchCAD validation set. \emph  {(a) BenchCAD val OOD --- IoU vs.\ training step.} The IID-trained run (green) climbs steadily to IoU $\sim $0.65 on its own held-out distribution by 25k steps. The OOD run (red) --- trained on a mixture excluding the targeted family slice --- plateaus near IoU $\sim $0.30 by 10k steps and shows little further improvement, leaving a $\sim $35-point gap to the IID ceiling. The HQ-only baseline (grey), trained without any BenchCAD-Synth data, fails to rise above IoU $\sim $0.10 across the full horizon. \emph  {(b) BenchCAD val OOD --- Essential-op pass rate.} The IID run reaches $\sim $0.85 essential-op pass rate, demonstrating that the underlying backbone is fully capable of producing the required operations once it has seen them in training. The OOD run improves to $\sim $0.35 but plateaus, leaving a $\sim $50-point gap. The HQ-only baseline stays at $\sim $0\% throughout --- the \textbf  {Op Vocabulary Gap}: a model whose SFT corpus omits helix, sweep, loft, twist-extrude, and parametric involute-gear operations never emits them, regardless of training compute. Together these curves position the BenchCAD generalisation gap as a benchmark-grade open problem: the deficit is not optimisation budget (curves saturate by 15--20k steps), not backbone capacity (same Qwen2-VL-2B reaches IID IoU 0.65 and essential-op pass 0.85), and not training-corpus operation coverage alone (the OOD run \emph  {has} BenchCAD-Synth data and still plateaus 35--50 points below IID) --- it is the fundamental difficulty of training large models to construct industry-grade parametric CAD code on \emph  {unseen} family distributions, which BenchCAD is designed to measure.}}{19}{figure.7}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:generalisation_gap}{{7}{19}{\textbf {The generalisation gap on BenchCAD remains substantial, even after 25k SFT steps.} Qwen2-VL-2B trained on three data mixtures under matched 9 GPU-hour budgets and evaluated throughout the 0--25k step horizon on the BenchCAD validation set. \emph {(a) BenchCAD val OOD --- IoU vs.\ training step.} The IID-trained run (green) climbs steadily to IoU $\sim $0.65 on its own held-out distribution by 25k steps. The OOD run (red) --- trained on a mixture excluding the targeted family slice --- plateaus near IoU $\sim $0.30 by 10k steps and shows little further improvement, leaving a $\sim $35-point gap to the IID ceiling. The HQ-only baseline (grey), trained without any BenchCAD-Synth data, fails to rise above IoU $\sim $0.10 across the full horizon. \emph {(b) BenchCAD val OOD --- Essential-op pass rate.} The IID run reaches $\sim $0.85 essential-op pass rate, demonstrating that the underlying backbone is fully capable of producing the required operations once it has seen them in training. The OOD run improves to $\sim $0.35 but plateaus, leaving a $\sim $50-point gap. The HQ-only baseline stays at $\sim $0\% throughout --- the \textbf {Op Vocabulary Gap}: a model whose SFT corpus omits helix, sweep, loft, twist-extrude, and parametric involute-gear operations never emits them, regardless of training compute. Together these curves position the BenchCAD generalisation gap as a benchmark-grade open problem: the deficit is not optimisation budget (curves saturate by 15--20k steps), not backbone capacity (same Qwen2-VL-2B reaches IID IoU 0.65 and essential-op pass 0.85), and not training-corpus operation coverage alone (the OOD run \emph {has} BenchCAD-Synth data and still plateaus 35--50 points below IID) --- it is the fundamental difficulty of training large models to construct industry-grade parametric CAD code on \emph {unseen} family distributions, which BenchCAD is designed to measure}{figure.7}{}}
